         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">He had always been close to him, behaving with care. ... Then now ... pointing to Supriya</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">says to Sunetra: || in [the tune] <hi>pañcam</hi> || “This one [is] a jewel of patience for me, [and he is] strongly approved of by me: in his power standing on top of the wishes,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2 #a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">This is a jewel of patience for me, [and it is] strongly honoured by me: in its power standing on top of the wishes.29 We will not let it become weak, [but] we will let our own heart[s] be silent. We will not be able to be …30 in the occasions of the sorrows. (Georges-Jean Pinault, p.c.)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>660</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">we will not let this one become weak, [but] we will let our own heart[s] be silent. We will not be able to be [his] enemy (?) [even] in the occasions of the sufferings." Thereupon</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the Bodhisattva ...-mitra, looking at the Bodhisattva Kusuma with an insatiable gaze, says: || in [the tune] meñameṃ || “Though not much praised, this</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">what is named compassion [karuṇā] has to be proclaimed as the most excellent of all. It realises the ... (work) of the Omniscient more readily and more helpfully than anything. [If] he sees the sufferings of the beings, ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... of the sufferings. 1. ... pleasant things, not at that time.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... with his own self, even unto (that). The life ..., the energy ... [2c] Who ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... this thought, through this one this companion will not ..." 2. Thereupon, having arrived in the palace, and learned (lit. understood) about the matter of letting rain jewels by Supriya,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the <hi>Śuddhavāsa</hi> gods say to each other: “Now it is time for us to go to our own dwelling.” Having just finished saying this, in an instant</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the surface of the air ... . Having seen this, the <hi>Kāmāvacara</hi> gods, the sky being empty, [say:] “for us also it is time</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">to go each to his own place.” For them the matter is finished here and now. Thereupon these gods disappeared over there. Thereupon Supriya, surrounded by his company,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">began to go to the place where he ought to stay [and] he came to his own re(sidence). Having entered inside with glad and joyful mind, he (greets?/is greeted by?) his relatives ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">The metre here always has the subcolon division 4+3; therefore, the last colon in 1d has to be restored to <hi>cämpem</hi> + monosyllabic (<hi>wes</hi> is the most likely) and to a monosyllabic word beginning with <hi>s</hi> and ending with a single consonant making a ligatura with the nasal of <hi>nessi</hi>. A possibilty would be <hi>sān</hi> 'enemy'.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment">The word separation <hi>śyetärccaṃ – kkana</hi> is very uncertain. Since the subcolon division is consistently 4+3, -<hi>kkana</hi> maybe the end of a tri-syllabic word that can be the plural of a substantive or of an adjective connected with <hi>läklenta</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">The mentioning of the leaving of all the gods recalls the commonplace dramaturgical indication at the end of an act or scene.</note></p>
